<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A lot of this relies upon the concept of free will.  And this has been debated at least as far back as Plato.<br>
<br>
Taked a person and put them in a suitation and see what choice they made.  Now rewind time and let them make a choice again.  If they make the same choice then they had no free will and were destined to make that choice.  If they changed their answer (say some kind of quantum probability) then free will is just randomness that arbitrarily dictates our life path.<br>
<br>
Humans have shown nothing inherient that makes them have to be more than complex machines.  Our brains are very intricate computers that work in a massively parallel capacity.  The goals of our brain is rooted in emotions which can be traced to hormones and neural wiring.<br>
<br>
The basic idea is we operate within the realm of physics.  If so we operate on a cause/effect basis.  In such a system there is no free will since everything is just a reaction.  Some come up with a soul to try to explain something beyone cause/effect physics and to explain free will.  However, properties of the soul become cumbersome.  Does a soul have memory?  Do souls jump from one body to the next (are they original)?  How does a soul transcend physics?  When you make claims of what a soul can do, you enter it into the realm of science and predictions can be made.<br>
<br>
If for some reason we have free will (whatever that can mean) and it is beyond God to predict, then he does not have the moral authority to judge us.  Say a man dies at age 50 and goes to hell for not repenting.  If he had lived to age 55, he may have repented and could have gone to heavan.  Since God cannot predict this and is omnipotent, then by allowing this man to die at age 50, God has judged what he does not know.<br>
<br>
