&quot;-Space and Time is a system that exists by itself. &quot;<br>
<br>
Space-time is relative to observers. Without observers there would be no space-time in and off itself. Space and time are much like colors, tastes, sounds, smells, and textures. All of which are contingent upon observers.<br>
<br>
&quot;-Social laws potentially exist by themselves...&quot;<br>
<br>
I disagree. Social laws have no existence at all. One can't coherently speak of a social law existing in and of itself.<br>
<br>
&quot;-Order and Chaos are derivadives(bad spelling) of Space and Time. &quot;<br>
<br>
Order and Chaos are perceptions. There is no such thing as &quot;order or chaos&quot; with out individuals.<br>
<br>
&quot;-Love and Truth is God's law.&quot;<br>
<br>
Love is an emotion. &quot;Truth&quot; winds up to be what the community of thinkers agree upon. <br>
<br>
The rest of your ideas rest upon the analogy you use between space-time and love/truth. I still don't follow the correlation you want to draw here or its relevance to what I have stated.<br>
<br>
What I have gotten from what you are saying is that we have Free Will and that because we have free will there is morality. Without choice we would be automatons and there would not be a moral world.<br>
<br>
If you think about this a moment (not that you haven't at all, I mean now) you might wonder what the first humans were like before the Tree of knowledge of Good and Evil was made available to them. Were they just automatons? They apparently had no &quot;choice&quot; so morals didn't exist, from what you are saying. If such was the case then why did god want to change that? Because he loves us? Does that make sense? Couldn't he have loved automatons? Doesn't he love monkeys and lizards, etc? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  If god created the fruit (a means to sin; hence exercise free will and create morality) because he wanted his creation to choose to love him, then isn't he a moral monster? After all, much pain has been the result of his little act just so he could get some loving. Seems pretty egocentric to me.<br>
